    <exercise workspace="1 in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain the meaning of <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to 3} f(x) = -2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>  
<ol>
      <li><!-- #2 -->
        <p>If <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to 2} g(x) = 7</m>, then 
        <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to 2^-} g(x)</m> <fillin/>.</p>
      </li>

      <li><!-- #3 -->
        <p>If <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to 8^-} h(x) = \frac{2}{3}</m> and 
        <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to 8^+} h(x) = -\frac{4}{3}</m>, then 
        <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to 8} h(x)</m> <fillin/>.</p>
      </li>

      <li><!-- #4 -->
        <p>If <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to -6^-} p(x) = \sqrt{5}</m> and 
        <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to -6^+} p(x) = \sqrt{5}</m>, then 
        <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to -6} p(x)</m> <fillin/>.</p>
      </li>
      
      <li><!-- #5 -->
        <p>If <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to 0^-} h(x) = e</m>, what do we know about 
        <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to 0} h(x)</m>?</p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </worksheet>
<!-- .............................................SECTION 2................................................. -->
<section>
  <title>Let Us Get Our Hands On!</title>
    <ol>
      <li><!-- #1 -->
        <p>Complete the graph below so <m>f(x)</m> has the domain <m>[-8,7]</m>, <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \rightarrow -4} f(x)=-2</m>, 
          and <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \rightarrow 5^-} f(x)=9</m>. </p>
      </li>

      <li><!-- #2 -->
        <p>Complete the tables below to estimate  <m>\displaystyle\lim_{t \rightarrow 0} \frac{|t-5|}{t}</m> numerically. 
          If the limit does not exist, state so and use limit notation to describe any infinite behavior. Round your answers to four decimal places (if necessary).
        <table>
          <title>Left-hand limit</title>
          <tabular halign="center">
            <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
              <cell>Variable <m>t</m></cell>
              <cell>Variable <m>f(t)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-0.1</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-0.01</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-0.001</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-0.0001</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>

        <table>
          <title>Right-hand limit</title>
          <tabular halign="center">
            <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
              <cell>Variable <m>t</m></cell>
              <cell>Variable <m>f(t)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-0.1</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-0.01</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-0.001</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-0.0001</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>


        </p>
      </li>

      <li><!-- #3 -->
        <p> Set up a table to estimate <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow -2} \frac{x^2-x-6}{(x+2)(x+7)}</m> numerically. 
          When creating your table, show at least three <m>x</m>-values approaching <m>-2</m> from each side and their corresponding function values in the table. 
          If the limit does not exist, state so and use limit notation to describe any infinite behavior. 
          Round your answers to four decimal places (if necessary). </p>
      </li>

      <li><!-- #4 -->
        <p> Given the graph of <m>f(x)</m> below and <m>g(x)=\frac{10x-30}{x^2-x-6}</m>, find <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \rightarrow 3} \left( \frac{f(x)+5x}{2}+\sqrt{g(x)+14} \right)</m>. </p>
      </li>

      <li><!-- #5 -->
        <p>Given <m>f(x) = \{ 5^{4x-3} \text{ if } x \leq -5, \frac{x^2-x}{x^2+2x} \text{ if } x > -5 \}</m></p>
      </li>

      <li><!-- #6 -->
        <p>Find the following limits algebraically. If the limit does not exist, state so and use limit notation to describe any infinite behavior. 
          Round your answers to four decimal places (if necessary).  </p>
      </li>

      <li><!-- #7 -->
        <p>For each graph below, find the indicated limit.  </p>
      </li>

      <li><!-- #8 -->
        <p>Jenn is trying to find <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \rightarrow \infty} f(x)</m> given  <m>f(x) = \frac{12+4x^7+x}{-19x^6+2x^2-5x^7}</m>. </p>
      </li>

    </ol>
</section>
<!-- .............................................SECTION 3................................................... -->
<section>
<title>Now...Grades Go Up!</title>
    <ol>
      <li><!-- #1 -->
        <p>The mathematical notation <m>\displaystyle\lim \limits_{x \rightarrow 5} f(x)</m> means <m>\underline{ \qquad\qquad}</m></p>
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li> <p>we need to find the value of the function  at <m>x=5</m>.</p> </li>
          <li> <p> we need to investigate the <m>y</m>-values of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> gets very near <m>x=5</m> from both the left and right sides of <m>x=5</m>, 
            but not necessarily at <m>x=5</m>.</p> </li>
          <li> <p>we need to find the horizontal asymptotes. </p> </li>
          <li> <p> we need to find the instantaneous rate of change.</p> </li>
          <li> <p> we need to investigate the <m>y</m>-values as we approach <m>x=5</m> only on the right side.</p> </li>
        </ol> 
      </li>

      <li><!-- #2 -->
        <p>Find <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\rightarrow 2^-} \frac{3x^2}{x^2-4}</m>. If the limit does not exist, but has infinite behavior, use limit notation to 
          describe the infinite behavior of the function as <m>x \longrightarrow 2^-</m>.</p>
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle {\lim_{x\rightarrow 2^-} \frac{3x^2}{x^2-4}}=3</m></p> </li>
          <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x\rightarrow 2^-} \frac{3x^2}{x^2-4}}=-\infty</m></p> </li>
          <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x\rightarrow 2^-} \frac{3x^2}{x^2-4}}</m> DNE, 
            but has infinite behavior that can be described as <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x \rightarrow 2^-} f(x) \rightarrow -\infty}</m>. </p> </li>
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x\rightarrow 2^-} \frac{3x^2}{x^2-4}}</m> DNE, 
            but has infinite behavior that can be described as <m>\displaystyle{\lim_{x \rightarrow 2^-} f(x) \rightarrow \infty}</m>. </p> </li>
          <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle {\lim_{x\rightarrow 2^-} \frac{3x^2}{x^2-4}}=0</m> </p> </li>
        </ol>
      </li>

      <li><!-- #3 -->
        <p>Find <m>\displaystyle\lim \limits_{x \rightarrow 7} \frac{x^2-8x+7}{x-7}</m>.</p>
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li> <p> <m>0</m> </p> </li>
          <li> <p> DNE </p> </li>
          <li> <p> <m>6</m>  </p> </li>
          <li> <p> <m>8</m> </p> </li>
          <li> <p> None of these. </p> </li>
        </ol>
      </li>

    </ol>
The graph of <m>f(x)</m> is not continuous at <m>x=2</m> because .25in0.05mm  I.
<m>f(2)</m> is not defined.
II.
<m>\D{\lim_{x\rightarrow 2} f(x)}</m> does not exist.
III.
<m>f(2) \neq \D{\lim_{x\rightarrow 2} f(x)}.</m>
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>
      I and III only
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      III only
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      II and III only
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      I, II, and III
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      II only
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>







</section>

